Problem 1: Rotating Machinery Diagnosis

Mechanical systems are always vibrating when operating. So, vibration analysis is one of the most popular and conventional ways to diagnose the mechanical system. In this problem, we are going to use the logistic regression algorithm to identify abnormality of a mechanical system.

Data information

  • File format: npy

  • Information: signal, label

  • Sampling rate: 12,800 Hz

  • File length (time): 0.78 sec

  • Labels based on one-hot encoding

    • A (Normal): [1,0]
    • B (Abnormal): [0,1]

  • label

Now, we need to extract features from the raw signal.

  • Use the following statistical features
    • peak, rms, kurtosis, crest factor, impulse factor, shape factor, skewness, smr, peak-peak

The equations are as follows:

$$\begin{align*} \text{Peak Value } &= \max_{n = 1, \dots, N} x_n \\ \\ \text{RMS } &= \sqrt{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N x_n^2} \\ \\ \text{Kurtosis } &= \frac{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N (x_n-\bar{x})^4}{\text{Var}^2} \\ \\ \text{Var } &= \frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N (x_n-\bar{x})^2 \\\\ \text{Crest Factor } &= \frac{\text{Peak}}{\text{RMS}}\\\\ \text{Impulse Factor } &= \frac{\text{Peak}}{\text{Mean}} \\ \\ \text{Mean } &= \frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N \lvert x_n \rvert \\\\ \text{Shape Factor } &= \frac{\text{RMS}}{\text{Mean}}\\\\ \text{Skewness } &= \frac{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N(x_n-\bar{x})^3}{\text{Var}^{3/2}}\\\\ \text{SMR } &= \left(\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=1}^N\sqrt{x_n} \right)^2 \\\\ \text{Peak-Peak Value } &= \max_{n = 1, \dots, N} x_n-\min_{n = 1, \dots, N} x_n \end{align*}$$$$x_i: \text{signal data}$$


The function for feature extraction is already ready for you. The function input and output are data $x$ and horizontally stacked feature vector, respectively.

In[4]:
def extfeat(x):
    fvector = []
   
    # time domain feature
    peak = np.max(np.abs(x))
    fvector.append(peak)
   
    rms = np.sqrt(np.mean(x**2))
    fvector.append(rms)
   
    kurtosis = scipy.stats.kurtosis(x)
    fvector.append(kurtosis)
   
    crest_factor = fvector[0]/fvector[1]
    fvector.append(crest_factor)
    
    impulse_factor = fvector[0]/(np.sum(np.abs(x))/len(x))
    fvector.append(impulse_factor)
    
    shape_factor = fvector[1]/(np.sum(np.abs(x))/len(x))
    fvector.append(shape_factor)

    skewness = scipy.stats.skew(x)
    fvector.append(skewness)
   
    smr = (np.sum(np.sqrt(np.abs(x)))/len(x))**2
    fvector.append(smr)
   
    pp = np.max(x) - np.min(x)
    fvector.append(pp)
   
    return fvector

feature_name = ['Peak', 'RMS', 'Kurtosis', 'Crest Factor', 'Impulse Factor','Shape Factor','Skewness','SMR', 'Peak-Peak']

# Your code here

# Encoder Structure
encoder = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation = 'relu', input_shape = (9,)),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(2, activation = None)
    ])

# Decoder Structure
decoder = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation = 'relu', input_shape = (2,)),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(9, activation = None)
    ])

# Autoencoder = Encoder + Decoder
autoencoder = tf.keras.models.Sequential([encoder, decoder])
In[10]:

Now, we want to generate new data with CVAE (Conditional Variational Autoencoder) !

3) Define the structure, loss, and model of the CVAE and train the CVAE.

'Variational' part is given below. (Refer to Problem 2 in PS#06)

In[6]:
# Your code here for the structure of CVAE
#
n_pixels = np.prod(train_i.shape[1:])
train_ii = train_i.reshape((len(train_i), n_pixels))
test_ii = test_i.reshape((len(test_i), n_pixels))
train_labeli = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(train_label)
test_labeli = tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(test_label)
n_x = train_ii.shape[1]
n_y = train_labeli.shape[1]
# Define the input
#
X = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(n_x,))
label = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(n_y,))
inputs = tf.keras.layers.concatenate([X,label])


# Define encoder
#
encoder_h = tf.keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu')(inputs)
mu = tf.keras.layers.Dense(2, activation='linear')(encoder_h)
l_sigma = tf.keras.layers.Dense(2, activation='linear')(encoder_h)


# Sampling latent space (you may change the code below so that the function fits your variables)
def sample_z(args): # a function that adds random normal noise -'variational' part 
    mu, l_sigma = args
    eps = tf.keras.backend.random_normal(shape=(50, 2), mean=0., stddev=1.)
    return mu + tf.keras.backend.exp(l_sigma / 2) * eps

z = tf.keras.layers.Lambda(sample_z, output_shape = (2, ))([mu, l_sigma])
zc = tf.keras.layers.concatenate([z, label])

# Define decoder
#
decoder_hidden =  tf.keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu')
decoder_out =  tf.keras.layers.Dense(784, activation='sigmoid')
h_p = decoder_hidden(zc)
outputs = decoder_out(h_p)
In[7]:
# Your code here for the loss of CVAE
#
def cae_loss(y_true, y_pred):
    recon = tf.keras.backend.sum(tf.keras.backend.binary_crossentropy(y_true, y_pred), axis=-1) # what will be the reconstruction error?
    kl = 0.5 * tf.keras.backend.sum(tf.keras.backend.exp(l_sigma) + tf.keras.backend.square(mu) - 1. - l_sigma, axis=-1) #you don't have to worry about this part
    return recon + kl
In[8]:
# Your code here for the entire model of CVAE
#
cvae = tf.keras.models.Model([X, label], outputs)
encoder = tf.keras.models.Model([X, label], mu)

d_in = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(2+n_y,))
d_h = decoder_hidden(d_in)
d_out = decoder_out(d_h)
decoder = tf.keras.models.Model(d_in, d_out)
In[9]:
# Your code here for the training of CVAE
#
cvae.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=0.001), loss=cae_loss)
cvae_hist = cvae.fit([train_ii, train_labeli], train_ii, verbose = 1, batch_size=50, epochs=500)

# Your code here

def construct_numvec(digit, z = None):
    out = np.zeros((1, 2 + n_y))
    out[:, digit + 2] = 1.
    if z is None:
        return(out)
    else:
        for i in range(len(z)):
            out[:,i] = z[i]
        return(out)

Problem 3: Data Defect

This problem is to demonstrate the importance of the class activation map

Let's consider a situation. Prof. Lee wanted a deep learning model that classifies digit '7' and '9'. However, when the student A was collecting image data for those two digits, some malfunction happened and resulted defects on all digit '9' images. Unforetunately, student A had no idea that his collected data had defects and trained the model with that data. After training his model, he achieved over 90% accuracy in the binary classification with his validation dataset. So, he gave the model to Prof. Lee. Prof. Lee with his own data that have no defects, testsed the model made by the student A. The model's test accuracy was very low! Such situation happened because the student A never plotted the class activation map for his validation dataset. The student A should have checked the region where the model focuses on when making the classification decision.



1) Load the training dataset provided above

  • Download CAM defect train image.npy

  • Download CAM defect train label.npy

  • Seperate the training dataset into train:validation in the ratio of 9:1

  • Provided dataset is composed of MNIST images from two different classes
